Logs:
-----

-> Check logs regularly to stay updated on system activity.

-> Treat logs like a system diary capturing daily events.

-> Stored in plain text under '/var/log/' directory.

-> Record everything from system messages to scurity alerts.

Importance of Logs:
-------------------

-> Helps identify when and why problems occured.

-> Tracks system activity for troubleshooting issues.

-> Records user actions for auditing and security.

Common Log file locations:
--------------------------

-> /var/log/messages -> Non-designated (general) logs events.

-> /var/log/secure -> Authentication related logs

-> /var/log/cron -> Cron job related log events

-> /var/log/boot.log -> System boot related log events

-> /var/log/dmesg -> Hardware related log events, specially from kernel.

Log Management Services:
------------------------

    a. rsyslog
    
    b. journald

How to use 'journalctl' to view Logs:
-------------------------------------

-> To display the entire Log;

    # journalctl

*** Use arrow keys to move up and down. Press 'Q' key to exit.

-> To display log X no of minutes since current time:

    # journalctl --since "X minutes ago"

    Example:

        # journalctl --since "10 minutes ago"

-> How to view log entries between two specific dates:

    # journalctl --since "YYYY-MM-DD" --until "YYYY-MM-DD"

    Example:

        # journalctl --since "2026-04-21" --until "2026-04-24"

-> How to filter log entries from a specific service unit:

    # journalctl -u <unit-name>

    Example:

        # journalctl -u sshd    -> display log entries related to SSH service.

-> How to list log entries based on priority:

    # journalctl -p err

-> How to list recent boots:

    # journalctl --list-boots

-> How to check the previous boot records:

    # journalctl -b -1

-> How to check the current boot session logs:

     journalctl -b 0

-> To monitor real-time log records:

    # journalctl -f

-> How to list logs from previous boot, high priority error logs related to sshd:
   
    # journalctl -b -p err -u sshd


